<HEADLINE>
<P>
'SELF-ESTEEM IS EARNED' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am in agreement with Schmoker. "Groundless praise" may encourage complacency, 
but more importantly this form of patronizing behavior has no place in our 
educational system where it breeds contempt among its students. During the '60s 
this contempt was concerned with the "hypocrisy" reflected in middle-class 
values. It is disquieting to consider the ways in which our educators still 
encourage these same attitudes. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the onus of failure permeates middle-class values and teaches 
the young that "one can never do enough." The resulting stress leads many 
students to drop out, or to set lesser goals for themselves. Most parents want 
their children to go to college, and in particular those parents who never went 
to college themselves. These same people confuse what is "great about America" 
and what has been "good for Japan." 
</P>
<P>
The most unfair comparison to date concerns the test-score differences among 
Korean, and Japanese students, who score higher than American students in 
mathematics. The fact being many Far Eastern countries start winnowing out 
their lesser achievers in the lower grades. There is no room for the late 
bloomer, or the quirky genius to flower, for the term "self" as used in the 
Orient is something quite different from the "self" we refer to in Western 
culture. The fact that Korean students ranked themselves last in mathematics, 
when in fact they were first, demonstrates a lack of self-esteem by Western 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
What we call self-esteem is that quality which most often encourages a student 
to rebel, and it is the ideal behind the student movement for democracy in 
China. Self-esteem, in order to grow, must have self-expression. Yet many 
school administrators, well-schooled themselves in crisis management, have 
adopted a patronizing attitude which rewards mediocrity and breeds contempt. 
Yes, tougher standards apply, but fewer constraints as well, which seems to me 
to be the essence of the American experience. 
</P>
<P>
DAVID C. REUTTER 
</P>
<P>
Vista 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
