<HEADLINE>
<P>
PICK OF THE WEEK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Vista Docents hold free tours of the historic Vista Del Arroyo Hotel, now 
headquarters for the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals, at 10 a.m. on the third 
Friday of the month. Tours of the hotel, 125 S. Grand Ave., Pasadena, last an 
hour. 
</P>
<P>
The hotel was taken over by the Army during World War II and was later used for 
government offices. By 1978, it was in such disrepair that it was closed. 
</P>
<P>
When it was reopened as headquarters for the court in February, 1986, a group 
of lawyers' and judges' wives organized as the Vista Docents to conduct the 
tours. Renovation, which has cost $10 million, is continuing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Trisha Martin, president of Vista Docents, leads tour of the historic 
Vista Del Arroyo Hotel. LOU MACK / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
