<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO; 
</P>
<P>
PAY HIKES GRANTED CITY, WATER WORKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Granting 3% salary raises to nearly all city employees, the City Council on 
Tuesday adopted changes in job qualifications for about 100 positions in city 
hall and in the Capistrano Valley Water District. 
</P>
<P>
The changes in most cases resulted in upgrading job requirements, with a 
corresponding increase in salary level that did not cause any employees to lose 
pay, Assistant City Manager George Scarborough explained. 
</P>
<P>
City job descriptions are reviewed every five years for accuracy and are 
updated to incorporate additional duties and responsibilities performed by the 
employee, Scarborough said. 
</P>
<P>
The first version of revised job descriptions was presented to city employees 
three months ago and 33 descriptions were challenged in an appeal process. The 
contested positions were amended according to the employees' testimony, 
Scarborough said. 
</P>
<P>
The city employs 80 people and the water district, whose board of directors is 
the City Council, employs 23 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
