<P>
BILL INTRODUCED TO CUT CAPITAL GAINS TAXES, EXPAND IRAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two Republican senators, claiming support from the Bush Administration and more 
than half the Senate, introduced a bill today to cut capital gains taxes and 
expand tax-deferred Individual Retirement Accounts. 
</P>
<P>
"This plan provides opportunities and incentives for all Americans," Sen. 
William V. Roth Jr. (R-Del.) told a news conference. "It's good for both savers 
and investors. And it's good for America." 
</P>
<P>
President Bush campaigned last year on a pledge to cut capital gains taxes. 
Over objections of Democratic leaders, the House in September approved a 
reduction endorsed by the Administration. That legislation did not address 
IRAs. 
</P>
<P>
Sen. Bob Packwood (R-Ore.), co-sponsor of the bill, claimed to have between 55 
and 58 votes for it in the 100-member Senate. 
</P>
