<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHECK-CASHING RULES VIEWED AS FRAUD THREAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Merchants across the country are handling personal checks and credit card 
transactions in ways that may lead to fraud and invasion of privacy, a consumer 
group said today. 
</P>
<P>
The organization, Bankcard Holders of America, assailed the practice of many 
merchants requiring customers who pay for purchases with personal checks to 
provide a major credit card number and expiration date, plus a telephone 
number. This information is then written on the check. 
</P>
<P>
"Store clerks often pressure consumers into writing their bank card numbers on 
personal checks, but these consumers don't realize the potential danger in 
doing so," the group's director, Elgie Holstein, told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
He contended that "mail order fraud and application fraud are increasingly 
popular crimes, and placing this information (a card's number and expiration 
date) on a personal check enables a thief to make purchases or apply for credit 
in the customer's name." 
</P>
<P>
"Requiring customers to present a major credit card as identification, or even 
noting on the check that the consumer holds a Visa or MasterCard, can be an 
appropriate merchant practice," Holstein said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
